title: S Chair
material_technique:
Welded steel frame, with rush seat
The rush used was identified by Fred Rumsey (Botanist- Identification and Advisory Service, Angela Marmont Centre for UK Biodiversity, The Natural History Museum) on 28 February 2012 as:
"The larger piece taken from the Tom Dixon S-Bend chair (W.6 -1993) is a very good match for Schoenoplectus lacustris (L.) Palla - Common Club-rush or Bulrush. Given its diameter this is the only native British species that it could be, although it could have been a large non-native member of the Cyperaceae imported for the purpose. The stem section  however shows a considerable anatomical similarity to our S. lacustris specimens."

material_technique: Paper chair, scale prototype for nendo's 'Cabbage Chair'. This prototype was made from a roll of waste paper. To create the chair, a cut was made down the roll, to about half-way down its height. Individual sheets of paper were then pulled away from the roll, layer by layer. These sheets created a stable structure, suitable for sitting with the addition of any core or supports.

Notes from upholstery investigation 26.11.1979
The chair had had at least two previous top covers.
The upholstery was 'modern' throughout.
The frame had been closenailed several times at the bottom of the rails. Once only at the top.- these nails were larger size - indicating 18c
Large square nail shanks were found in the top and bottom holes and smaller square ones in the bottom row only.
All the upholstery was removed and it was clear that the chair has been completely re-upholstered once.
Several hand made tacks were found in the back rail with threads of the original black horsehair top cover.
The frame had been re-inforced at some time with corner blocks and an additional back rail and has the initials IM stamped on the underside of the original back rail.
